==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Frisian ''dōm'', Old Saxon ''dōm'', Old High German [[tuom]], Old Norse [[dómr]], Gothic [[𐌳𐍉𐌼𐍃]].  The Germanic source was from a stem verb originally meaning ‘to place, to set’ (a sense-development also found in Latin [[statutum]], Greek [[θεμις]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /do:m/

===Noun===
'''dōm''' ''[[Wiktionary Appendix:Old English strong declension|strong]] m''
# a [[law]], a [[statute]]
# a [[judgement]]

